04147nmm a2200601Ia 9781503638624DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036386247 a10.1515/97815036386242doi  a(DE-B1597)680253  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aQC495.8b.B49 2024 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a304.2223/eng/202310051 aBeyes, Timon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrganizing Color :bToward a Chromatics of the Social /cTimon Beyes. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSensing Media: Aesthetics, Philosophy, and Cultures of Media00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1 Something Winged: Color as Organizational Force -- t2 Weimar, ca. 1800: Cooking Chocolate -- t3 New Lanark, 1816: Working the Silent Monitor -- t4 Lower Bengal, 1859: The Coke of Empire -- t5 Berlin, 1924: Consuming the Color Chart -- t6 The Zone, 1945: Unleashing the Synthetic Rainbow -- t7 Paris, 1967: The Revolution Will Be Colorized -- t8 Houston, 1971: Two Kinds of Colorism -- t9 Cologne, 2007: The Distribution of the Insensible -- t10 Broken Tones: Toward a Chromatics of the Social -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe live in a world that is saturated with color, but how should we make sense of color's force and capacities? This book develops a theory of color as fundamental medium of the social. Constructed as a montage of scenes from the past two hundred years, Organizing Color demonstrates how the interests of capital, management, governance, science, and the arts have wrestled with color's allure and flux. Beyes takes readers from Goethe's chocolate experiments in search of chromatic transformation to nineteenth-century Scottish cotton mills designed to modulate workers' moods and productivity, from the colonial production of Indigo in India to globalized categories of skin colorism and their disavowal. Tracing the consumption, control and excess of industrial and digital color, other chapters stage encounters with the literary chromatics of Pynchon's Gravity's Rainbow processing the machinery of the chemical industries, the red of political revolt in Godard's films, and the blur of education and critique in Steyerl's Adorno's Grey. Contributing to a more general reconsideration of aesthetic capitalism and the role of sensory media, this book seeks to pioneer a theory of social organization—a "chromatics of organizing"—that is attuned to the protean and world-making capacity of color.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aColor (Philosophy). 0aColorxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aColor.  aaesthetics.  aart.  achromatics.  amedia.  aorganization theory.  aorganization.  asocial theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363862440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503638624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503638624/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles